18 make a one-time appropriation in the amount of $3 billion into such fund, which shall be
19 appropriated from the Revenue Shortfall Reserve. The General Assembly shall be
20 authorized, but not required, to appropriate additional amounts into such fund. All moneys
21 appropriated into the Georgia's Children First Trust Fund shall not be subject to the
22 provisions of Article III, Section IX, Paragraph IV(c), relating to the lapsing of funds, and
23 shall be used to provide scholarships, grants, or other forms of financial assistance for child
24 care services in this state; provided, however, that a portion of the moneys appropriated to
25 the Georgia's Children First Trust Fund shall be invested and reinvested in a manner as
26 provided by law. Moneys received from returns on such investments and reinvestments
27 shall be deposited into the Georgia's Children First Trust Fund and shall be used to provide
28 scholarships, grants, or other forms of financial assistance for child care services in this
29 state. The General Assembly shall be authorized to provide by law for any matters relating
30 to the purpose or provisions of this subparagraph."
31 SECTION 2.
32 The above proposed amendment to the Constitution shall be published and submitted as
33 provided in Article X, Section I, Paragraph II of the Constitution. The ballot submitting the
34 above proposed amendment shall have written or printed thereon the following:
35 "( ) YES Shall the Constitution of Georgia be amended so as to authorize the General
36 Assembly to use a portion of the state's historic, multiyear revenue surplus
37 ( ) NO to create a self-sustaining Georgia's Children First Trust Fund for the
38 purpose of providing access to child care services in this state?"
39 All persons desiring to vote in favor of ratifying the proposed amendment shall vote "Yes."
40 All persons desiring to vote against ratifying the proposed amendment shall vote "No." If
41 such amendment shall be ratified as provided in said Paragraph of the Constitution, it shall
42 become a part of the Constitution of this state.
